frm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://a676.g.akamai.net/f/676/987/12h/photos.netclubs.com/live/photos/h/s/1/i/1i2bjmpslb9h36b90188mmkcvg/bioh.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Global Warming</span><hr size=1> I listened to a radio show the other day that had a meteorologist hosting it, and he had two Climatologists as guests. The answer they gave to a question concerning Global Warming pleasantly surprised me.<br><br>Basically, they said that Global Warming does appear to be happening (the world is about 1 degree warmer than it was 100 years ago) – But, and here is the big but, we do not have enough information yet to say that it is wholly human in origin nor that it will be harmful. Likewise, we cannot say that humans are uninvolved or that it will be benign. <br><br>Also, while the globe, in general, is warmer – some regions are actually cooler. I live in the SE US, and it is about 1 degree cooler on average than it was 100 years ago. The reason for this regional anomaly does, according to the Climatologists I listened to, appear to be caused by humans. 100 years ago, this region was devoted to row crops such as cotton, and now large areas are forested. The ground cover has had the effect of reducing the temperature. Which makes me wonder if the increase in temperatures is more a factor of our removing ground cover than pollution?<br><br>They also mentioned the fact that we may be in a natural warming trend. And while this is also not definite, it is a strong possibility.<br><br>What we have are questions, and a lot of people on both sides taking junk science to support their ideas. <br><br>Now, we should try and reduce our emissions. Dumping toxins into the air and water is fundamentally stupid, even if we can see no discernable climatological effect from them.<br><br>Related and/or interesting sites:<br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nrc.gov/what-we-do/radiation/affect.html">NRC - How Does Radiation Affect the Public</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://lwf.ncdc.noaa.gov/oa/aasc/AASC-Policy-Statement-on-Climate.htm">AASC - Policy Statement on Climate Variability and Change</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://lwf.ncdc.noaa.gov/oa/climate/globalwarming.html">NCDC - Global Warming FAQ</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.gcrio.org/gwcc/misconceptions.html">GCRIO - Common misconceptions about climate change</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br><!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 0] --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif ALT="0]"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p>Dr. Carstairs</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/udrcarstairs.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DrCarstairs</A> at: 3/9/02 4:53:26 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 318<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/9/02 6:46:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Global Warming</span><hr size=1> Current scientific thinking is that we are involved with increasing global warming.  The brownlash movement are trying to discredit it but they aren't having any luck doing so through scientific channels.  Instead they're moving from science to politics, much like <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.quackwatch.com/01QuackeryRelatedTopics/hfreedom.html">quacks</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br><br>Whatever the probabity of that being right (probably higher then 90% at the moment) we should take action to prevent it from happening.  Probably the biggest problem with our environmental, health and safety regulations is that we've historically regualted by bodies.  Instead a more pro-active approach aimed at preventing the problems in the first place should be taken.  It's far better to reduce the danger then have people die later on.  As far as I'm concerned until something has been proven to have a reasonable safety and if relavant also a low negative environmental impact it shouldn't be used until it has been proven safe.<br><br>The standards for reasonable would depend on what exactly it is.  With things that would affect the earths environment it would be a pretty high standard of proof.  Coal would never pass it and even solar would have a hard time.  Nuclear would easily pass it (only one that could acutally the amount of electricity we'd need).<br><br>Those who think we should wait until it becomes a problem and then fix it should be given a guided tour of the former USSR and then told to clean the place up.  If they think we should wait until it becomes a problem because it isn't proven until it does then they can find another planet to experiment on although that isn't really neccessary because Venus makes a pretty good lab.<br><br>The biggest problem with global warming is the uncertainty.  We do know that we're probably increasing it although we aren't really all that sure by how much.  We also don't know what the exact effects will be or even how long it'll take.  The oceans have a very large heat storage capacity and are often thought to have a thousand year memory of temperature which means we may have done a lot more damage then we realise.  It would also mean that it would take a lot longer for any methods we use to fix the damage to work once it's done. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 653<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/16/02 5:42:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Global Warming</span><hr size=1> Whether or not the Earth is heating up is secondary to the 'fact' our air is less clean. Thankfully lead has been removed from cars in Australia now. An exhaust emmision which was proven to cause lower intelligence in children, particularly in smog prone larger cities.<br>Ofcourse, lead is only an additive and one of only hundreds of waste products known to be harmful that fossil fuel use dumps into our atmosphere. Billions of tons in poisons annually. Now one in four children have asthma. That is absolutely terrifying. Something has to be done. Unfortunately nothing can be done without an alternative. The only alternative we have is nuclear power but the insane greenies would rather we keep dumping toxins into the environment at a rate likely to crash a link in the food chain at some point.<br>Humans are highly dependant on their environment and being larger animals less adaptable than we imagine. If we continue damaging our world with chemicals now thought to disrupt genetic structure there will come a time when mother nature will simply collapse. Not entirely. Life is tenacious. Most of the lifeforms on this planet will persevere and the world will recover. It's just that larger more complex organisms such as us will vanish.<br>Either we go nuclear big time to support our ever growing energy needs or we persist with using coal, natural gas and oil until either we exhaust the supply or wipe ourselves out. Whichever happens first. These fossil fuels took millions of years to accumulate but we are using them up in mere decades. Nothing like this has ever happened to the Earth before and the environmental breaking point is anyones guess. What I do know is that the air is disgusting in many places. When you start to cough you know it is because you are ingesting fumes. We should stop using the Earth as a toilet and embrace nuclear power before it's too late.  <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 3/16/02 5:45:38 pm<br></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showPrevMessage?topicID=15.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showNextMessage?topicID=15.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15.topic&index=2><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.emailToFriend?topicID=15.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm10.threadControl?topicID=15.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/space/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a 